solution: Sum the first two equations to find $c+o+n=t.$ Solve the third equation for $c$ to find $c=s-t,$ and substitute $s-t$ for $c$ in $c+o+n=t$ to find $o+n+s-t=t\implies o+n+s=2t.$ Substitute $12$ for $o+n+s$ to find $t=12/2=\boxed{6}.$
steps:
Step 1: Rewrite the equations to isolate the variables:
\begin{align*}
o + c &= u \\
n + u &= t \\
c + t &= s \\
o + n + s &= 12
\end{align*}
Substitute the last equation into the fourth equation to obtain $o + n + (c + t) = 12.$

Step 2: Replace $s$ with $c+t$ in the third equation, and replace $o+n+s$ with $12$ in the fourth equation to obtain
\begin{align*}
o + c &= u \\
n + u &= t \\
c + t &= s \\
o + n + s &= 12
\end{align*}
\begin{align*}
o + c &= u \\
n + u &= t \\
c + t &= c + t \\
o + n + (c + t) &= 12
\end{align*}
Substitute $o + c = u$ into the first equation to obtain $u + n = t.$

\begin{align*}
o + c - o &= u - c \\
c &= u - c \\
2c &= u - c \\
2c + c &= u - c + c \\
3c &= u
\end{align*}
